&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">&lt;span style=" font-family:'Favorit'; font-size:12pt;">Here, one can see the Ottoman forces undertaking the colossal effort of transporting their ships over land to see them safely put out in the Golden Horn. This was ordered by Mehmed II because the Byzantine defenders had erected a colossal chain barrier across the water way to block ships from entering. Mehmed’s road of greased logs was not only a triumph of logistical organisation, but it dealt a severe blow to the defenders. With Ottoman ships prowling the waters, the movement of supplies by the Genoese in Pera, who were theoretically neutral, became more difficult still.&lt;/span>&lt;/p>&lt;/body>&lt;/html></text>
