<text>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd">
&lt;html>&lt;head>&lt;meta name="qrichtext" content="1" />&lt;style type="text/css">
p, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }
&lt;/style>&lt;/head>&lt;body style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;">
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">&lt;span style=" font-family:'Favorit'; font-size:12pt;">Broquière’s work is notoriously scant on architectural details of the city of Constantinople. Although he is keen to provide detailed information on the many churches in the city, his is a work less interested in the architectural fabric of the city. Rather, he is altogether more interested in the ecclesiastical mysteries contained with the churches, and of the people he encounters on his travels around the city.&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">&lt;span style=" font-family:'Favorit'; font-size:12pt;">However, some details are contained and evidently influenced this depiction, particularly the description of the city as, “having the form of a triangle, with one side bounded by the straits of St George”. Broquière also describes Constantinople’s landward defences. He estimates the length of the walls as being 6 miles from one side to the other, and he also records the deep ditch, the ‘en glacis’, that was a part of the defences.&lt;/span>&lt;/p>&lt;/body>&lt;/html></text>
