<text>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd">
&lt;html>&lt;head>&lt;meta name="qrichtext" content="1" />&lt;style type="text/css">
p, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }
&lt;/style>&lt;/head>&lt;body style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;">
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">Despite a rather frustrating lack of interest in the urban fabric of Constantinople, Broquière nevertheless dedicates a significant section of his description of the city to the church of Hagia Sophia. According to Broquière, this is not just one of the many “handsome” churches in the city, but it is the most remarkable. This is confirmed by the illustration, which uses the towering figure of Hagia Sophia as something of an iconic representation of the city. The artist however, is clearly not familiar with the shape and style of Orthodox churches. Whereas Broquière offers a clear description of the rounded shape of Hagia Sophia, the artist here has depicted the church in a much more recognizably European, almost Gothic style, notably in the great central rose window on the façade.&lt;/p>
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">Broquière’s description of the church appears to have been motivated by his own faith and curiosity; as a Catholic, Broquière confesses to being curious to attend an Orthodox service: “I was curious to witness the manner of the Greeks performing divine service”. He attended a service led by the Patriarch of Constantinople, the highest spiritual authority in Orthodoxy, and saw the imperial family attending the service at the same time. These included the Emperor John Paleologus VII, the predecessor of Constantine XI, the final Byzantine emperor.&lt;/p>
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">There could be few clearer indications as to the close relationship between secular power and religion in the Byzantine empire.&lt;/p>&lt;/body>&lt;/html></text>
