<text>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd">
&lt;html>&lt;head>&lt;meta name="qrichtext" content="1" />&lt;style type="text/css">
p, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }
&lt;/style>&lt;/head>&lt;body style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;">
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">Although Broquière was not witness to the siege, the depiction of Constantinople contained within this illustrated version of his work was clearly influenced by other contemporary sources. Here one can see clearly the impressive array of enormous cannon that the Sultan Mehmed II has arrayed against the Byzantine defenders. The illustration, through lacking in some details, nevertheless makes clear not only the vast size of these early cannons, but also the logistical considerations involved in directing their fire. They can be seen to necessitate being securely dug into the ground for instance. One is left to wonder whether one of Le Tavernier’s illustrations here is inspired by a report of Orban’s mighty Basilica cannon.&lt;/p>
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">It is also interesting to note in this depiction that the focus remains on the Ottoman army massing in the foreground, rather than the Christian defenders of Constantinople. Resplendent en-masse in golden armour, they stand in marked contrast to the distant and dwindling numbers of Byzantine defenders. &lt;/p>&lt;/body>&lt;/html></text>
